            <h1>A GUIDE TO GITHUB</h1>
            <p>GitHub was co-founded by Tom Preston-Werner, Chris Wanstrath, PJ Hyett, and Scott Chacon in 2008 as a platform to streamline collaboration among software developers. They built GitHub on Git, a version-control system created by Linus Torvalds in 2005. The co-founders envisioned a user-friendly platform where developers could collaborate seamlessly, managing code while integrating social networking features. As GitHub gained popularity, it became the go-to platform for open-source projects, empowering developers worldwide.</p>
            
            <h2>HISTORY</h2>
            <p>By 2012, GitHub had established itself as the primary hub for developers, hosting millions of projects. Microsoft acquired GitHub in 2018 for $7.5 billion, sparking debates on open-source future. However, the acquisition led to new tools like GitHub Actions and Codespaces, enhancing its capabilities. Today, GitHub remains the largest code-hosting platform, driving innovation and collaboration for developers worldwide.</p>
            
